const faqs = [{"question": "Which peptides help with sex drive?", "answer": "PT-141 (bremelanotide) is the peptide most directly used for sex drive because it acts on melanocortin receptors in the brain to increase desire itself, in both men and women. Where low sex drive is driven by hormonal decline, peptides that support the body's own hormonal signaling — or testosterone optimization — may be more appropriate first. Because the causes of low libido differ from person to person, the right peptide is determined by a physician evaluation, not a one-size-fits-all stack."}, {"question": "Can peptides treat erectile dysfunction?", "answer": "PT-141 can help a specific type of erectile dysfunction — the neurological, desire-driven kind. In studies, roughly one-third of men who did not respond to sildenafil (Viagra) achieved erections with PT-141. It is not a universal ED cure: erectile dysfunction that is primarily vascular is usually better addressed with PDE5 inhibitors or by treating the underlying cause. Because ED can be an early sign of cardiovascular disease, any new or persistent ED should be medically evaluated."}, {"question": "Are there peptides for low libido in women?", "answer": "Yes. PT-141, branded as Vyleesi, is FDA-approved for hypoactive sexual desire disorder (HSDD) in premenopausal women — one of the few approved treatments for low sexual desire in women. It targets the desire pathway in the brain rather than blood flow or lubrication, and is dosed on demand under physician supervision after evaluation for hormonal and other contributing causes."}, {"question": "Can peptides improve sexual performance?", "answer": "It depends on what you mean by performance. PT-141 improves desire and arousal by acting in the brain; it does not primarily improve the mechanics of erection the way PDE5 inhibitors (Viagra, Cialis) do. For many patients the limiting factor is desire rather than blood flow, which is where PT-141 fits. A physician can determine whether desire, vascular function, hormones, or a combination is driving the concern."}, {"question": "How is PT-141 different from Viagra or Cialis?", "answer": "PT-141 works through the central nervous system by activating melanocortin receptors in the brain, addressing the neurological component of sexual desire. Viagra and Cialis work peripherally by increasing blood flow to erectile tissue. PT-141 addresses desire (libido), while PDE5 inhibitors primarily address the mechanical aspect of erection."}, {"question": "Can women use PT-141?", "answer": "Yes. PT-141 (branded as Vyleesi) received FDA approval specifically for hypoactive sexual desire disorder (HSDD) in premenopausal women. It is one of the few FDA-approved treatments for female sexual dysfunction related to low desire."}, {"question": "How quickly does PT-141 work?", "answer": "PT-141 typically takes 30–60 minutes to take effect when administered subcutaneously. Effects can last several hours. Unlike PDE5 inhibitors, PT-141's effects on desire may be more gradual and subtle."}, {"question": "Is PT-141 safe to use with blood pressure medication?", "answer": "PT-141 does not interact with the nitric oxide pathway, making it generally safer to combine with blood pressure medications compared to PDE5 inhibitors. However, all medication interactions should be reviewed by your prescribing physician."}, {"question": "How often can PT-141 be used?", "answer": "Current prescribing guidelines recommend no more than one dose per 24 hours and no more than 8 doses per month. Your physician will determine the appropriate frequency based on your health profile and response."}, {"question": "Does PT-141 require a prescription?", "answer": "Yes. PT-141 is a prescription medication that requires physician evaluation and oversight. At Strong Health, our physicians conduct a thorough health assessment before prescribing any peptide therapy."}, {"question": "Can PT-141 be combined with other peptide therapies?", "answer": "In some cases, PT-141 may be part of a broader peptide protocol. For example, patients using growth hormone secretagogues for body composition may also benefit from PT-141 for libido support. All combinations require physician oversight."}];

